## 10. G.O.D (Gradients on Demand) - Distributed LLM/Diffusion Training

**GitHub:** https://github.com/gradients-ai/G.O.D  
**Subnet:** Unknown  
**Website:** github.com/gradients-opensource (winners repository)

### README Summary
G.O.D (Gradients on Demand) is a subnet for distributed intelligence for LLM and diffusion model training. Uses a tournament-based system where validators execute miners' open-source training scripts on dedicated infrastructure.

Key features:
- **Tournaments**: Competitive events lasting 4-7 days per tournament
- **Frequency**: New tournaments start 72 hours after previous one ends
- **Rewards**: Exponentially higher weight potential for top performers
- **Open Source**: Winning AutoML scripts are released when tournaments complete
- **Winners Repository**: First place scripts uploaded to github.com/gradients-opensource
- **Training Focus**: LLM and diffusion model training
- **GRPO**: Uses GRPO (Group Relative Policy Optimization) reward functions

Architecture:
- Validators execute miners' training scripts on dedicated infrastructure
- Miners submit open-source AutoML training scripts
- Scripts are evaluated on dedicated validator infrastructure
- Winners determined by training performance

### Littlefoot Suitability Analysis

**✅ PROS:**
- **EXTREMELY HIGH energy usage** - LLM and diffusion model training is one of the most power-intensive AI workloads
- **Latency-tolerant** - Tournaments last 4-7 days, training is batch process, not real-time
- **Infrastructure-based** - Validators execute scripts on dedicated infrastructure, location is verifiable
- **Tournament-based** - Discrete events (4-7 days) means location verification can happen per tournament
- **Open source scripts** - Transparency in training methods, easier to verify work
- **Dedicated infrastructure** - Validators run training on their infrastructure, location verification possible

**❌ CONS:**
- **Validator-executed** - Validators execute scripts on their infrastructure, not miners' infrastructure
- **Unknown subnet number** - Hard to assess current state/activity
- **Tournament model** - Discrete events might make continuous location verification more complex
- **Dedicated infrastructure** - If validators control infrastructure, miners don't control location (different from other training subnets)

**Verdict:** ⚠️ **MODERATE** - Training is extremely energy-intensive and latency-tolerant, BUT the architecture is different: validators execute scripts on their infrastructure, not miners'. This means location verification would need to verify validator infrastructure location, not miner infrastructure. This is a different model than Templar/IOTA where miners run training.

**Key Difference:** 
- **Templar/IOTA**: Miners run training on their infrastructure → verify miner location
- **G.O.D**: Validators run training on their infrastructure → verify validator location (different overlay target)

**Recommendation:** G.O.D might be better suited for a different overlay mechanism that targets validator infrastructure rather than miner infrastructure. Or, if miners provide the training scripts and validators execute them, there might be a way to verify where the training actually happens.

